  "text": "e clinical impact of the basophil activation test (BAT) is due to the unique ability of basophils to degranulate upon cross-linking of the speci c IgE (sIgE) bound on membrane-bound high a nity IgE-receptor (FcεRI) by allergen exposure. A er discovery of the quantal upregulation of CD63 during basophil activation in 1991 [CITATION_1] , the BAT was developed in the 1990s [CITATION_2] . CD63 is a membrane protein localized to the same secretory lysosomal granule that contains histamine. Translocation of CD63 to the cell membrane during degranulation can be measured by ow cytometry. BAT (like skin prick test, SPT) re ects a functional response as basophil (or skin mast cell) activation can be induced by cross-linking of FcεRI.",
